rleden","1180–Male":"1180–Overleden","1180–Female":"1180–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1160–Female":"1160–Overleden","about 1180":"circa 1180","1200":"1200","about 1200":"circa 1200","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1180–":"about 1180–Deceased","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","about 1180":"about 1180","1200":"1200","about 1200":"about 1200","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Torrell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: (i) nickname from Old French  <i>torel</i> ‘young bull’.  See also  Torr  . Some of the bearers below may belong under (2). (ii) variant of   Turrell  .","2  English: locative name for someone who lived or worked at a lime kiln or a malt kiln (Middle English  <i>torel</i>, Old French  <i>toraile</i> ‘little tower, kiln’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tyrrell","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): perhaps a nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>tirer</i> ‘to pull’, in the same sense as French <i>Tirand</i> ‘one who pulls on the reins’, hence ‘obstinate, stubborn’. This name may have become confused with   Turrell  . A branch of this Anglo-Norman family has been in Ireland since the 12th century. Its name has been Gaelicized as <b>Tirial</b>.","English: habitational name from Tirril (Cumbria), which derives from Old Norse <i>tyri</i> ‘resinous wood’ + <i>erg</i> ‘shieling’."]},{"name":"Thorold","meanings":["English: relationship name from the Anglo-Norman and Middle English personal name  <i>T(h)urold</i>,  <i>T(h)orold</i>,  <i>T(h)orald</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>Þóraldr</i>). The initial  <i>T</i> is due to the Anglo-Norman pronunciation of  <i>Th-</i>.  <i>Torald</i> and  <i>Torold</i> became  <i>Toraud</i> and  <i>Toroud</i>, giving the modern surname  <i>Torode</i>. This name may have become confused with   Tyrrell  ,   Turrill  , and   Torrell  ."]},{"name":"Turrell","meanings":["English (southeastern and East Anglia):","most frequently an Anglo-Norman French pronunciation of <i>Thorold</i> (Old Norse <i>Thóraldr</i>, from the elements <i>Thórr</i> ‘Thor’ + <i>valdr</i> ‘power, rule’). This name and that in 2 may have become confused with   Tyrrell  .","from Middle English <i>T(h)urild</i> (Old Norse <i>Thórhildr</i>, <i>Thorild</i>, the latter a rare woman's name from the divine name <i>Thórr</i> ‘Thor’ + <i>hildr</i> ‘battle’)."]},{"name":"Torr","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>tor(re)</i> ‘rocky peak, hill’ (Old English <i>torr</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on or by a hill, or toponymic, from a place so named, such as <i>Torre</i>, the earlier name of Torquay (Devon). The element is especially common in placenames in southwestern England, particularly Devon, but it is occasionally found in other English regions, such as Sussex and Derbyshire.","nickname for someone thought to resemble a bull, from Old French <i>tor</i> (from Latin <i>taurus</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Unknown Torrell was born about 1180, his father, William Torrell `the Naperer', was 22 and his mother, Unknown, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Unknown."},"et":{"about 1180–":"umbes 1180–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1200":"1200","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1180–":"noin 1180–Kuollut","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","about 1180":"noin 1180","1200":"1200","about 1200":"noin 1200","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1180–":"environ 1180–Décédé","1